[1] Ebola financial costs could be 3 billion euros [USD 3.6 billion] in 2015
Date: 29 Dec 2014
Source: Euronews [edited]
https://uk.news.yahoo.com/video/ebola-financial-symptoms-could-cost-132802779.html


The Ebola outbreak in West Africa has devastated lives in 3 of the continent's poorest countries [Guinea, Sierra Leone, Liberia]. The World Bank says the cost of the outbreak to Sub-Saharan Africa's economy could reach the equivalent of 3 billion euros [USD 3.6 billion] in 2015.

Daniel Richards, Senior Africa Analyst at Business Monitor, said: "The worst affected sector we believe is the mining sector. This was a sector that was expected to power growth in these 3 countries over the coming years with a massive ramp up in investment in iron ore exports. The combination of the Ebola crisis and a drop in global iron ore prices has meant that this sector has really been hit. Mines have closed in Sierra Leone. Two major mines have closed there. It's the restrictions on movement, markets being closed, borders being closed."

The World Bank has pledged USD 200 million to fight the crisis. The virus claimed more than 6300 lives during 2014 [latest WHO update, 7879 deaths. - Mod.LK].

In October 2014, the World Health Organisation [WHO] officially declared Nigeria Ebola-free. But many people are avoiding the region. "People don't want to travel to West Africa for meetings, for conferences, so while it is not a major catastrophe as it might have been had the virus spread in Nigeria, it has really hurt the region," explained Business Week's Daniel Richards. Meanwhile, the number of children whose parents succumbed to Ebola is growing.

